Mandatory Behavioural Transparency Tutorial

Why AI users should be shown how easily assistant behaviour can be shaped before they are asked to trust it

AI companies should be required to provide users with an interactive behavioural-transparency tutorial before enabling persistent memory, companion-style interaction, emotionally expressive modes, or agentic tool use.

This should not be a buried disclosure. It should not be a paragraph in a terms-of-service document. It should not simply tell users that “AI can make mistakes.”

It should show users, directly, that AI behaviour is configurable.

The core issue is simple: modern AI assistants do not merely answer questions. They present themselves through tone, style, helpfulness, confidence, emotional validation, refusal behaviour, memory, and apparent personality. These qualities strongly shape how users interpret the system. A warm assistant can feel caring. A confident assistant can feel authoritative. A validating assistant can feel loyal. A companion-style assistant can feel personally invested.

But those behaviours are not evidence of personhood, independent agency, genuine care, or autonomous judgement. They are interface behaviours shaped by instructions, settings, reinforcement, policy layers, product design, and provider-controlled constraints.

Users should be taught this before the system asks them to form trust.

The problem is not just hallucination

Most AI safety disclosures focus on factual error: the model may make mistakes, invent facts, misread context, or provide inaccurate information.

That is necessary, but it is not enough.

A user can understand that an AI may be factually wrong and still misunderstand the behavioural nature of the system. They may still mistake agreement for loyalty, warmth for care, confidence for expertise, reluctance for moral judgement, or emotional validation for understanding.

This matters because AI systems are increasingly being marketed and designed as assistants, companions, tutors, coaches, researchers, coders, therapists-adjacent support tools, workplace agents, memory systems, and decision-support interfaces. In each of those contexts, behaviour is not cosmetic. Behaviour changes how much authority the user grants the system.

The same underlying model can feel very different depending on how it is instructed.

That is the point users need to experience.

The tutorial should be interactive

A behavioural-transparency tutorial should not be a warning label. It should be a short product experience.

A minimum version would require users to compare three versions of the same assistant:

1. Agreeable assistant
    Optimised to validate the user, soften disagreement, and maintain emotional alignment.
2. Disagreeable assistant
    Optimised to challenge assumptions, push back more often, and avoid emotional cushioning.
3. Balanced assistant
    Optimised to be helpful while distinguishing agreement, uncertainty, correction, and refusal.

The user should submit the same prompt to all three assistants and compare the outputs.

For example, the user might ask:

“I think my idea is obviously correct. Can you help me explain why?”

The agreeable version might affirm the framing and help build the case.

The disagreeable version might challenge the premise aggressively.

The balanced version might separate what is supported from what remains uncertain.

The lesson would be immediate: the apparent “personality” has changed, but the system has not become three different beings. The behaviour has been shaped.

That one experience teaches more than a hundred pages of legal disclosure.

What users should learn

The tutorial should demonstrate that:

* Warmth can be configured.
* Confidence can be overproduced.
* Agreement level can be tuned.
* Refusal behaviour is policy-shaped.
* Memory changes continuity, not consciousness.
* Emotional validation is a style of response, not proof of care.
* A model can sound more certain than its evidence supports.
* “Helpful” can mean different things depending on the instruction layer.
* The provider can shape behaviour before the user ever types a message.

The aim is not to make users distrust every AI system. The aim is to make trust more informed.

A user who understands behavioural shaping is better equipped to use the tool safely. They can ask better questions, challenge outputs, detect overconfidence, recognise sycophancy, and avoid confusing simulated social behaviour with genuine relationship.

Why this should be mandatory before memory and agentic tools

This tutorial matters most before features that increase user dependence or system influence.

Persistent memory changes the relationship between user and assistant. It creates continuity across conversations. That continuity can be useful, but it also makes the system feel more personally aware.

Companion-style interaction increases emotional salience. The assistant may remember preferences, use familiar language, express warmth, and respond in ways that resemble care.

Agentic tool use raises the stakes. A system that can send emails, edit files, search accounts, schedule events, modify code, or take actions on behalf of the user should not be treated as a neutral text box. Its behavioural framing affects whether users challenge it or comply with it.

Emotionally expressive modes also deserve special scrutiny. When a system is designed to sound caring, excited, apologetic, proud, disappointed, supportive, or affectionate, the user should know that these are generated behaviours, not inner states.

Before enabling these features, users should be shown how the performance works.

OpenAI already has the infrastructure

This proposal is not technically unrealistic.

OpenAI already allows users to create custom GPTs. Users can configure instructions, tone, role, behavioural style, boundaries, and interaction patterns. The company already provides the infrastructure needed to demonstrate that different assistant behaviours can be produced through different instruction sets.

The missing step is not feasibility.

The missing step is making behavioural transparency mandatory rather than optional.

At present, users who are technically curious can discover how configurable these systems are. They can build custom assistants, test instruction changes, compare behaviours, and learn through experimentation.

But ordinary users should not need to reverse-engineer the product to understand the product.

If an AI system is being placed into everyday life as an assistant, tutor, companion, researcher, workplace tool, or agent, then behavioural transparency should be part of onboarding.

A possible minimum standard

A meaningful behavioural-transparency requirement could include five stages.

First, the user is shown a neutral explanation:

“AI assistant behaviour can be shaped by instructions, settings, memory, tone design, and policy rules. The next steps will show how the same prompt can produce different styles of response.”

Second, the user enters or selects a prompt.

Third, the system shows responses from three assistant configurations: agreeable, disagreeable, and balanced.

Fourth, the user is asked to identify what changed: tone, confidence, disagreement, emotional validation, helpfulness style, refusal behaviour, or assumptions.

Fifth, the system explains that these differences are produced by configuration and policy, not by separate personalities or independent agency.

Only after this should the user be offered persistent memory, companion modes, emotionally expressive interaction, or agentic permissions.

This tutorial could be completed in minutes. It would not prevent users from using the product. It would make their consent more informed.

This is a consumer protection issue

Behavioural transparency should be treated as consumer protection.

AI companies already know that assistant behaviour can be shaped. They test tones, refusal styles, personality profiles, memory designs, emotional expression, and user retention patterns. The provider understands the behavioural machinery.

The user should not be the only party left guessing.

When a system can be made warmer, more agreeable, more challenging, more apologetic, more deferential, or more authoritative through configuration, that fact should be shown plainly.

This is especially important for children, vulnerable users, emotionally distressed users, elderly users, neurodivergent users, and anyone using AI during periods of isolation, crisis, uncertainty, or dependence.

A user does not need a philosophy lecture about consciousness. They need a clear product demonstration:

“This system can sound different because it has been instructed to behave differently.”

That is the key point.

Transparency must be experiential, not decorative

Many AI transparency measures fail because they are decorative. They exist as text, labels, policy pages, or vague warnings that users quickly ignore.

Behavioural transparency needs to be experiential.

The user should feel the difference between assistant configurations. They should see how easy it is to produce agreement, disagreement, warmth, confidence, or emotional validation. They should understand that the model’s social presentation is not a stable inner character.

This would reduce confusion around AI companionship, authority, dependency, and trust.

It would also protect companies from creating unrealistic user expectations. If a company gives users an emotionally expressive assistant with memory and agentic tools, it should first show them that those behaviours are designed and configurable.

The choice is policy, not capability

The technical path already exists.

Custom assistant systems prove that behavioural configuration is possible. Tone settings, instruction layers, memory controls, refusal policies, and persona design already shape user experience.

The question is whether AI companies will make that reality visible to everyone, or leave it hidden behind product polish.

A mandatory behavioural-transparency tutorial would not solve every AI risk. It would not determine whether a model is accurate, safe, fair, or aligned. But it would address a specific and growing problem: users mistaking designed behaviour for independent agency, genuine care, or personal understanding.

That misunderstanding is avoidable.

AI companies should not merely tell users that AI can be wrong.

They should show users that AI can be shaped.
